WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:15.240
In 1942, Albert Einstein was teaching at Oxford University and one day he just gave an exam

00:15.240 --> 00:20.240
of physics to his senior class of physics students and he was walking on the campus with his

00:20.240 --> 00:25.240
assistant and all of a sudden the assistant looked at Albert Einstein and said, Dr. Einstein,

00:25.240 --> 00:32.200
this exam which you just gave to the senior class of physics students, isn't that exactly the

00:32.200 --> 00:39.200
same exam you gave to exactly the same class one year ago? Yeah, yeah, yeah,

00:39.200 --> 00:44.680
said Albert Einstein, it's exactly the same. But Dr. Einstein, how could you possibly do

00:44.680 --> 00:57.400
that? The assistant said, well, said Einstein, the answers have changed. The answers have

00:57.400 --> 01:02.880
changed. In other words, what is true for 1942 is even more true for today. We live in a world

01:02.880 --> 01:07.240
where the questions might be the same, but the answers have changed. In other words,

01:07.240 --> 01:13.000
what has got you here will no longer get you there. And if you want to have results that

01:13.000 --> 01:16.920
you've never had before, well, you need to start doing things you've never done before.

